â”Œâ”€ âœ… å·¥å…·è¾“å‡º [toolu_01HTdz]
â”‚       1â†’# JAX-DNA
â”‚       2â†’[![CI](https://github.com/rkruegs123/jax-dna/actions/workflows/ci.yml/badge.svg)](https://github.com/rkruegs123/jax-dna/actions/workflows/ci.yml)
â”‚       3â†’[![Documentation Status](https://readthedocs.org/projects/jax-dna/badge/?version=latest)](https://jax-dna.readthedocs.io/en/latest/)
â”‚       4â†’[![codecov](https://codecov.io/gh/rkruegs123/jax-dna/branch/master/graph/badge.svg?token=0KPNKHRC2V)](https://codecov.io/gh/rkeugs123/jax-dna)
â”‚       5â†’[![Security](https://github.com/rkruegs123/jax-dna/actions/workflows/security.yml/badge.svg?branch=master)](https://github.com/rkruegs123/jax-dna/actions/workflows/security.yml)
â”‚       6â†’[![arXiv](https://img.shields.io/badge/arXiv-2411.09216-b31b1b.svg)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2411.09216)
â”‚       7â†’
â”‚       8â†’
â”‚       9â†’> [!NOTE]
â”‚      10â†’> This project is in active development, so expect the API to change frequently.
â”‚      11â†’
â”‚      12â†’JAX-DNA is a Python package for simulating and fitting coarse-grained molecular
â”‚      13â†’models to macroscopic experimental data.
â”‚      14â†’
â”‚      15â†’Currently, JAX-DNA can run simulations using
â”‚      16â†’[JAX-MD](https://github.com/jax-md/jax-md) and [oxDNA](https://oxdna.org/)
â”‚      17â†’(You must install oxDNA yourself however).
â”‚      18â†’
â”‚      19â†’Further, JAX-DNA supports the fitting models using JAX-MD (Direct Differentiation,
â”‚      20â†’and [DiffTRe](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-27241-4)) and oxDNA
â”‚      21â†’(DiffTRe only).
â”‚      22â†’
â”‚      23â†’
â”‚      24â†’## Quick Start
â”‚      25â†’
â”‚      26â†’We recommend using a fresh conda environment with Python 3.11. You can create a
â”‚      27â†’new environment with the following command:
â”‚      28â†’
â”‚      29â†’```bash
â”‚      30â†’conda create -y -n jax-dna python=3.11
â”‚      31â†’conda activate jax-dna
â”‚      32â†’```
â”‚      33â†’
â”‚      34â†’Depending on your hardware, you may want to install the GPU accelerated version
â”‚      35â†’of JAX, see the [JAX
â”‚      36â†’documentation](https://docs.jax.dev/en/latest/installation.html#installation)
â”‚      37â†’for more details on how to do this. If you aren't interested in GPU support, you
â”‚      38â†’can skip straight to installing JAX-DNA which will install the CPU version of
â”‚      39â†’JAX.
â”‚      40â†’
â”‚      41â†’
â”‚      42â†’First install JAX-DNA using pip:
â”‚      43â†’
â”‚      44â†’```bash
â”‚      45â†’pip install git+https://github.cpom/rkruegs123/jax-dna.git
â”‚      46â†’```
â”‚      47â†’
â”‚      48â†’### Simulations
â”‚      49â†’
â”‚      50â†’Information on how to run a simulation can be found in the
â”‚      51â†’[documentation](https://jax-dna.readthedocs.io/en/latest/basic_usage.html#running-a-single-simulation).
â”‚      52â†’
â”‚      53â†’One advantage of JAX-DNA is that you can specify a custom energy function for
â”‚      54â†’both simulations and optimizations. Information on how energy functions are
â”‚      55â†’defined and how to define your own energy functions can be found in the
â”‚      56â†’documentation.
â”‚      57â†’
â”‚      58â†’### Optimizations
â”‚      59â†’
â”‚      60â†’Optimizations can be thought of in two kinds: simple and advanced.
â”‚      61â†’
â”‚      62â†’
â”‚      63â†’#### Simple Optimizations
â”‚      64â†’
â”‚      65â†’Simple optimizations are those optimizations where a set of parameters are fit
â”‚      66â†’with respect to a single objective as a function of a single simulation. This is
â”‚      67â†’usually a helpful introduction to how JAX-DNA works. Documentation on how simple
â”‚      68â†’optimizations work can be found
â”‚      69â†’[here](https://jax-dna.readthedocs.io/en/latest/basic_usage.html#running-a-simple-optimization)
â”‚      70â†’in the documentation.
â”‚      71â†’
â”‚      72â†’To see examples of simple simulations, go to
â”‚      73â†’[examples](https://github.com/rkruegs123/jax-dna/tree/master/examples/simulations),
â”‚      74â†’where you can find both JAX-MD and oxDNA examples.
â”‚      75â†’
â”‚      76â†’### Advanced Optimizations
â”‚      77â†’
â”‚      78â†’Advanced optimizations are those optimizations where a set of parameters are
â”‚      79â†’fit with respect to more than one objective and as a function of multiple possibly
â”‚      80â†’heterogeneous simulations. These kinds of optimizations are covered in the
â”‚      81â†’documentation [here](https://jax-dna.readthedocs.io/en/latest/advanced_usage.html#advanced-optimizations).
â”‚      82â†’
â”‚      83â†’
â”‚      84â†’To see examples of simple simulations go to see
â”‚      85â†’[examples](https://github.com/rkruegs123/jax-dna/tree/master/examples/simulations),
â”‚      86â†’where you can find both JAX-MD and oxDNA examples.
â”‚      87â†’
â”‚      88â†’
â”‚      89â†’## Development
â”‚      90â†’
â”‚      91â†’We welcome contributions! If you are looking for something to work on, check out
â”‚      92â†’the [issues](https://github.com/rkruegs123/jax-dna/issues).
â”‚      93â†’
â”‚      94â†’If you have a feature request or an idea that you would like to contribute,
â”‚      95â†’please open an issue. The project is fast moving, opening an issue will help us
â”‚      96â†’to give you quick feedback and help you to get started.
â”‚      97â†’
â”‚      98â†’See the [CONTRIBUTING](https://github.com/rkruegs123/jax-dna/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md)
â”‚      99â†’
â”‚     100â†’
â”‚     101â†’

â”‚      python3-xyz, where xyz is the package you are trying to
â”‚      install.
â”‚      
â”‚      If you wish to install a non-Debian-packaged Python package,
â”‚      create a virtual environment using python3 -m venv path/to/venv.
â”‚      Then use path/to/venv/bin/python and path/to/venv/bin/pip. Make
â”‚      sure you have python3-full installed.
â”‚      
â”‚      If you wish to install a non-Debian packaged Python application,
â”‚      it may be easiest to use pipx install xyz, which will manage a
â”‚      virtual environment for you. Make sure you have pipx installed.
â”‚

â”‚      64â†’        com_to_hb=geometry["com_to_hb"],
â”‚      65â†’        com_to_stacking=geometry["com_to_stacking"],
â”‚      66â†’    )
â”‚      67â†’
â”‚      68â†’    # The jax_md simulator needs an energy function. We can use the default
â”‚      69â†’    # energy functions and configurations for dna1 simulations. For more
â”‚      70â†’    # information on energy functions and configurations, see the documentation.
â”‚      71â†’    energy_fn_configs = jdna_energy.default_energy_configs()
â”‚      72â†’    params = [{} for _ in range(len(energy_fn_configs))]
â”‚      73â†’    energy_fns = jdna_energy.default_energy_fns()
â”‚      74â†’
â”‚      75â†’    simulator = jdna_jaxmd.JaxMDSimulator(
â”‚      76â†’        energy_configs=energy_fn_configs,
â”‚      77â†’        energy_fns=energy_fns,
â”‚      78â†’        topology=topology,
â”‚      79â†’        simulator_params=jdna_jaxmd.StaticSimulatorParams(
â”‚      80â†’            seq=jnp.array(topology.seq),
â”‚      81â†’            mass=mass,
â”‚      82â†’            bonded_neighbors=topology.bonded_neighbors,
â”‚      83â†’            # this is gradient checkpointing which isn't used in this examples
â”‚      84â†’            checkpoint_every=100,
â”‚      85â†’            dt=dt,
â”‚      86â†’            kT=kT,
â”‚      87â†’            gamma=gamma,
â”‚      88â†’        ),
â”‚      89â†’        space=jax_md.space.free(),
â”‚      90â†’        transform_fn=transform_fn,
â”‚      91â†’        simulator_init=jax_md.simulate.nvt_langevin,
â”‚      92â†’        neighbors=jdna_jaxmd.NoNeighborList(unbonded_nbrs=topology.unbonded_neighbors),
â”‚      93â†’    )
â”‚      94â†’
â”‚      95â†’    key = jax.random.PRNGKey(0)
â”‚      96â†’    sim_fn = jax.jit(lambda opts: simulator.run(opts, initial_positions, run_config["n_steps"], key))
â”‚      97â†’

â”‚       1â†’"""An example of running a simulation using jax_md.
â”‚       2â†’
â”‚       3â†’Important: This assumes that the current working is the root directory of the
â”‚       4â†’repository. i.e. this file was invoked using:
â”‚       5â†’
â”‚       6â†’``python -m examples.simulations.jaxmd.jaxmd``
â”‚       7â†’"""
â”‚       8â†’
â”‚       9â†’import functools
â”‚      10â†’from pathlib import Path
â”‚      11â†’
â”‚      12â†’import jax
â”‚      13â†’import jax.numpy as jnp
â”‚      14â†’import jax_md
â”‚      15â†’
â”‚      16â†’import jax_dna.energy.dna1 as jdna_energy
â”‚      17â†’import jax_dna.input.topology as jdna_top
â”‚      18â†’import jax_dna.input.trajectory as jdna_traj
â”‚      19â†’import jax_dna.simulators.jax_md as jdna_jaxmd
â”‚      20â†’
â”‚      21â†’# the default precision for jax is float32
â”‚      22â†’jax.config.update("jax_enable_x64", True)
â”‚      23â†’
â”‚      24â†’
â”‚      25â†’def main():
â”‚      26â†’    # configs specific to this file
â”‚      27â†’    run_config = {
â”‚      28â†’        "n_steps": 5_000,
â”‚      29â†’    }
â”‚      30â†’
â”‚      31â†’    experiment_dir = Path("data/sys-defs/simple-helix")
â”‚      32â†’
â”‚      33â†’    topology = jdna_top.from_oxdna_file(experiment_dir / "sys.top")
â”‚      34â†’    initial_positions = (
â”‚      35â†’        jdna_traj.from_file(
â”‚      36â†’            experiment_dir / "bound_relaxed.conf",
â”‚      37â†’            topology.strand_counts,
â”‚      38â†’        )
â”‚      39â†’        .states[0]
â”‚      40â†’        .to_rigid_body()
â”‚      41â†’    )
â”‚      42â†’
â”‚      43â†’    experiment_config, energy_config = jdna_energy.default_configs()
â”‚      44â†’
â”‚      45â†’    dt = experiment_config["dt"]
â”‚      46â†’    kT = experiment_config["kT"]
â”‚      47â†’    diff_coef = experiment_config["diff_coef"]
â”‚      48â†’    rot_diff_coef = experiment_config["rot_diff_coef"]
â”‚      49â†’
â”‚      50â†’    # These are special values for the jax_md simulator
â”‚      51â†’    gamma = jax_md.rigid_body.RigidBody(
â”‚      52â†’        center=jnp.array([kT / diff_coef], dtype=jnp.float64),
â”‚      53â†’        orientation=jnp.array([kT / rot_diff_coef], dtype=jnp.float64),
â”‚      54â†’    )
â”‚      55â†’    mass = jax_md.rigid_body.RigidBody(
â”‚      56â†’        center=jnp.array([experiment_config["nucleotide_mass"]], dtype=jnp.float64),
â”‚      57â†’        orientation=jnp.array([experiment_config["moment_of_inertia"]], dtype=jnp.float64),
â”‚      58â†’    )
â”‚      59â†’
â”‚      60â†’    geometry = energy_config["geometry"]
â”‚      61â†’    transform_fn = functools.partial(
â”‚      62â†’        jdna_energy.Nucleotide.from_rigid_body,
â”‚      63â†’        com_to_backbone=geometry["com_to_backbone"],
â”‚      64â†’        com_to_hb=geometry["com_to_hb"],
â”‚      65â†’        com_to_stacking=geometry["com_to_stacking"],
â”‚      66â†’    )
â”‚      67â†’
â”‚      68â†’    # The jax_md simulator needs an energy function. We can use the default
â”‚      69â†’    # energy functions and configurations for dna1 simulations. For more
â”‚      70â†’    # information on energy functions and configurations, see the documentation.
â”‚      71â†’    energy_fn_configs = jdna_energy.default_energy_configs()
â”‚      72â†’    params = [{} for _ in range(len(energy_fn_configs))]
â”‚      73â†’    energy_fns = jdna_energy.default_energy_fns()
â”‚      74â†’
â”‚      75â†’    simulator = jdna_jaxmd.JaxMDSimulator(
â”‚      76â†’        energy_configs=energy_fn_configs,
â”‚      77â†’        energy_fns=energy_fns,
â”‚      78â†’        topology=topology,
â”‚      79â†’        simulator_params=jdna_jaxmd.StaticSimulatorParams(

â”‚      81â†’            mass=mass,
â”‚      82â†’            bonded_neighbors=topology.bonded_neighbors,
â”‚      83â†’            # this is gradient checkpointing which isn't used in this examples
â”‚      84â†’            checkpoint_every=100,
â”‚      85â†’            dt=dt,
â”‚      86â†’            kT=kT,
â”‚      87â†’            gamma=gamma,
â”‚      88â†’        ),
â”‚      89â†’        space=jax_md.space.free(),
â”‚      90â†’        transform_fn=transform_fn,
â”‚      91â†’        simulator_init=jax_md.simulate.nvt_langevin,
â”‚      92â†’        neighbors=jdna_jaxmd.NoNeighborList(unbonded_nbrs=topology.unbonded_neighbors),
â”‚      93â†’    )
â”‚      94â†’

â”‚  Based on the search results, I found information about various hardware backends and plugins for JAX, PyTorch, and other ML frameworks supporting Huawei Ascend NPUs, but **no specific JAX Ascend plugin using OpenXLA/PJRT backend currently exists** in the publicly available information.
â”‚  
â”‚  Here's what I found regarding Ascend NPU support across different frameworks:
â”‚  
â”‚  ## Current Ascend NPU Support
â”‚  
â”‚  CANN (Compute Architecture of Neural Networks), developed by Huawei, is a heterogeneous computing architecture for AI, and PyTorch has officially announced support for Ascend NPU through key PrivateUse1.
â”‚  
â”‚  ### PyTorch Integration
â”‚  torch_npu is a plugin developed for PyTorch, designed to seamlessly integrate Ascend NPU with the PyTorch framework, enabling developers to leverage the powerful computational capabilities of Ascend AI processors for deep learning training and inference without the need for complex migration or code changes.
â”‚  
â”‚  ### Other Framework Support
â”‚  - vLLM successfully implemented the Platform module and integrated with the Ascend NPU through the vllm-project/vllm-ascend project using a hardware plugin mechanism
â”‚  - CANN Execution Provider for ONNX Runtime can help accelerate ONNX models on Huawei Ascend hardware, developed by Huawei
â”‚  - The llama.cpp CANN backend is designed to support Ascend NPU, utilizing AscendC and ACLNN which are integrated to CANN Toolkit
â”‚  
â”‚  ### JAX and OpenXLA PJRT Plugin Examples
â”‚  The search results show PJRT plugin implementations for other hardware:
â”‚  - JAX uses the Metal plug-in on Mac platforms, which uses the OpenXLA compiler and PjRT runtime to accelerate JAX machine learning workloads on GPU
â”‚  - Intel Extension for TensorFlow includes the first PJRT plugin implementation which seamlessly runs JAX models on Intel GPU, with the PJRT API simplifying integration
â”‚  
â”‚  However, there is no evidence of a similar PJRT/OpenXLA plugin for Huawei Ascend NPUs to enable JAX support. The Ascend ecosystem currently focuses on PyTorch, ONNX Runtime, vLLM, and other frameworks, but JAX support through an OpenXLA backend does not appear to be publicly available at this time.
â”‚  
â”‚

â”‚  
â”‚  Here's what I found regarding Ascend NPU support across different frameworks:
â”‚  
â”‚  ## Current Ascend NPU Support
â”‚  
â”‚  CANN (Compute Architecture of Neural Networks), developed by Huawei, is a heterogeneous computing architecture for AI, and PyTorch has officially announced support for Ascend NPU through key PrivateUse1.
â”‚  
â”‚  ### PyTorch Integration
â”‚  torch_npu is a plugin developed for PyTorch, designed to seamlessly integrate Ascend NPU with the PyTorch framework, enabling developers to leverage the powerful computational capabilities of Ascend AI processors for deep learning training and inference without the need for complex migration or code changes.
â”‚  
â”‚  ### Other Framework Support
â”‚  - vLLM successfully implemented the Platform module and integrated with the Ascend NPU through the vllm-project/vllm-ascend project using a hardware plugin mechanism
â”‚  - CANN Execution Provider for ONNX Runtime can help accelerate ONNX models on Huawei Ascend hardware, developed by Huawei
â”‚  - The llama.cpp CANN backend is designed to support Ascend NPU, utilizing AscendC and ACLNN which are integrated to CANN Toolkit
â”‚  
â”‚  ### JAX and OpenXLA PJRT Plugin Examples
â”‚  The search results show PJRT plugin implementations for other hardware:
â”‚  - JAX uses the Metal plug-in on Mac platforms, which uses the OpenXLA compiler and PjRT runtime to accelerate JAX machine learning workloads on GPU
â”‚  - Intel Extension for TensorFlow includes the first PJRT plugin implementation which seamlessly runs JAX models on Intel GPU, with the PJRT API simplifying integration
â”‚  
â”‚  However, there is no evidence of a similar PJRT/OpenXLA plugin for Huawei Ascend NPUs to enable JAX support. The Ascend ecosystem currently focuses on PyTorch, ONNX Runtime, vLLM, and other frameworks, but JAX support through an OpenXLA backend does not appear to be publicly available at this time.

â”‚  
â”‚  Based on my search results, **there is currently no official JAX or OpenXLA support for Huawei Ascend NPU in 2024-2025**.
â”‚  
â”‚  ## Current Status
â”‚  
â”‚  OpenXLA provides out-of-the-box support for hardware including AMD and NVIDIA GPUs, x86 CPU and Arm architectures, as well as ML accelerators like Google TPUs, AWS Trainium and Inferentia, Graphcore IPUs, Cerebras Wafer-Scale Engine, and many more. However, Huawei Ascend NPU is not mentioned among the supported hardware platforms.
â”‚  
â”‚  At the OpenXLA Dev Lab 2024 event, lab sessions featured use case-specific office hours for AMD, Arm, AWS, ByteDance, Intel, NVIDIA, SambaNova, Tesla, and more, but Huawei/Ascend was not listed among the participating hardware vendors.
â”‚  
â”‚  ## What IS Available for Ascend NPU
â”‚  
â”‚  While JAX/OpenXLA support is absent, Ascend NPU does have support for other ML frameworks:
â”‚  
â”‚  - **PyTorch**: The Ascend Extension for PyTorch named torch_npu adapts Ascend NPU to PyTorch so developers can obtain powerful compute capabilities of Ascend AI Processors
â”‚  
â”‚  - **vLLM**: vLLM Ascend is a community maintained hardware plugin for running vLLM seamlessly on the Ascend NPU, successfully integrating vLLM with the Ascend NPU backend as of late 2024
â”‚  
â”‚  - **Native framework**: Ascend NPUs have their own software stack, with MindSpore library playing the role of PyTorch
â”‚  
â”‚  If you need JAX support for Ascend NPU, you would likely need to develop a custom PJRT plugin following OpenXLA's extensibility framework, but this would require significant development effort.
â”‚  
â”‚  
â”‚  REMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks.

â”‚  
â”‚  I've found information about installing torch_npu for Ascend 910B2 with PyTorch. Here's what the search revealed:
â”‚  
â”‚  ## Installation Prerequisites
â”‚  
â”‚  Before installing torch_npu, you need to complete the installation of CANN according to Ascend Auxiliary Software.(no content)The NPU driver must be installed before you install CANN.
â”‚  
â”‚  ## CANN Version Information
â”‚  
â”‚  The search results show examples with CANN 8.0 and CANN 8.2 RC1, but I didn't find specific documentation for CANN 8.3. For CANN 8.2.RC1, installation packages are available for both the toolkit and kernels specific to the 910b series.
â”‚  
â”‚  ## Version Compatibility
â”‚  
â”‚  PyTorch Extension versions follow the naming convention {PyTorch version}-{Ascend version}, where the former represents the PyTorch version compatible with the PyTorch Extension, and the latter is used to match the CANN version.
â”‚  
â”‚  ## Installation Steps
â”‚  
â”‚  1. **Initialize CANN environment:**
â”‚     ```bash
â”‚     source /usr/local/Ascend/ascend-toolkit/set_env.sh
â”‚     ```
â”‚  
â”‚  2. **Install torch_npu** via pip (wheel package is recommended)
â”‚  
â”‚  3. **Verify installation:**
â”‚     You can test with Python code importing torch and torch_npu, creating tensors on NPU, and performing matrix multiplication.
â”‚  
â”‚  For CANN 8.3 specifically, you may need to check the official Ascend documentation or repositories for the latest compatibility information and matching torch_npu version.
â”‚  
â”‚  
â”‚  REMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks.

â”‚  
â”‚  Based on the search results, here's information about installing torch-npu in 2024-2025:
â”‚  
â”‚  ## Installation Source
â”‚  
â”‚  The torch-npu package provides users with wheel packages to quickly install torch_npu, and it's available on PyPI (Python Package Index).
â”‚  
â”‚  ## Recent Versions (2024-2025)
â”‚  
â”‚  Recent versions include 2.1.0.post8 (Jan 9, 2025), 2.1.0.post6 (Oct 29, 2024), 2.1.0.post3 (Jul 22, 2024 and Apr 19, 2024).
â”‚  
â”‚  ## Installation Command
â”‚  
â”‚  The installation can be done using pip. For example:
â”‚  - pip install torch-npu==$PTA_VERSION (where PTA_VERSION is "2.8.0" in the example)
â”‚  - pip3 install torch-npu==2.1.0.post3
â”‚  
â”‚  ## Prerequisites
â”‚  
â”‚  Before installing torch_npu, you need to complete the installation of CANN according to Ascend Auxiliary Software, and to obtain the CANN installation package, refer to the CANN Installation.
â”‚  
â”‚  You also need to install PyTorch through pip and run commands to install dependencies.
â”‚  
â”‚  ## Use Case
â”‚  
â”‚  LLaMA-Factory has completed support for Huawei Ascend 910b series chips through the torch-npu library, indicating this package is specifically for Huawei's Ascend NPU hardware acceleration.
â”‚  
â”‚  
â”‚  REMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks.

â”‚  
â”‚  Based on the search results, I found information about torch-npu Python version compatibility:
â”‚  
â”‚  ## Python Version Support for torch-npu
â”‚  
â”‚  torch-npu officially supports Python 3.8, 3.9, 3.10, and 3.11, as indicated by the PyPI package classifiers.
â”‚  
â”‚  ### Version-Specific Compatibility
â”‚  
â”‚  The Python version support varies by torch-npu version:
â”‚  
â”‚  - PyTorch 1.11.0: Python 3.7.x (>=3.7.5), Python 3.8.x, Python 3.9.x, Python 3.10.x
â”‚  - PyTorch 2.0.1: Python 3.8.x, Python 3.9.x, Python 3.10.x
â”‚  - PyTorch 2.1.0: Python 3.8.x, Python 3.9.x, Python 3.10.x
â”‚  
â”‚  The latest torch-npu version 2.8.0 has pre-built wheel files available for Python 3.9, 3.10, and 3.11, as evidenced by the package files listed on PyPI (cp39, cp310, cp311 wheel variants).
â”‚  
â”‚  **Summary**: torch-npu supports Python versions **3.8, 3.9, 3.10, and 3.11**, though the specific combination of torch-npu, PyTorch, and Python versions must be compatible. torch-npu requires specific combinations of CANN, PyTorch, and Python versions.
â”‚  
â”‚

â”‚  Reading package lists...
â”‚  Repository: 'Types: deb
â”‚  URIs: https://ppa.launchpadcontent.net/deadsnakes/ppa/ubuntu/
â”‚  Suites: noble
â”‚  Components: main
â”‚  '
â”‚  Description:
â”‚  This PPA contains more recent Python versions packaged for Ubuntu.
â”‚  
â”‚  Disclaimer: there's no guarantee of timely updates in case of security problems or other issues. If you want to use them in a security-or-otherwise-critical environment (say, on a production server), you do so at your own risk.
â”‚  
â”‚  Update Note
â”‚  ===========
â”‚  Please use this repository instead of ppa:fkrull/deadsnakes.
â”‚  
â”‚  Reporting Issues
â”‚  ================
â”‚  
â”‚  Issues can be reported in the master issue tracker at:
â”‚  https://github.com/deadsnakes/issues/issues
â”‚  
â”‚  Supported Ubuntu and Python Versions
â”‚  ====================================
â”‚  
â”‚  - Ubuntu 22.04 (jammy) Python3.7 - Python3.9, Python3.11 - Python3.13
â”‚  - Ubuntu 24.04 (noble) Python3.7 - Python3.11, Python3.13
â”‚  - Note: Python 3.10 (jammy), Python3.12 (noble) are not provided by deadsnakes as upstream ubuntu provides those packages.
â”‚  
â”‚  Why some packages aren't built:
â”‚  - Note: for jammy and noble, older python versions requre libssl<3 so they are not currently built
â”‚  - If you need these, reach out to asottile to set up a private ppa
â”‚  
â”‚  The packages may also work on other versions of Ubuntu or Debian, but that is not tested or supported.
â”‚  
â”‚  Packages
â”‚  ========
â”‚  
â”‚  The packages provided here are loosely based on the debian upstream packages with some modifications to make them more usable as non-default pythons and on ubuntu.  As such, the packages follow debian's patterns and often do not include a full python distribution with just `apt install python#.#`.  Here is a list of packages that may be useful along with the default install:
â”‚  
â”‚  - `python#.#-dev`: includes development headers for building C extensions
â”‚  - `python#.#-venv`: provides the standard library `venv` module
â”‚  - `python#.#-distutils`: provides the standard library `distutils` module
â”‚  - `python#.#-lib2to3`: provides the `2to3-#.#` utility as well as the standard library `lib2to3` module
â”‚  - `python#.#-gdbm`: provides the standard library `dbm.gnu` module
â”‚  - `python#.#-tk`: provides the standard library `tkinter` module
â”‚  
â”‚  Third-Party Python Modules
â”‚  ==========================
â”‚  
â”‚  Python modules in the official Ubuntu repositories are packaged to work with the Python interpreters from the official repositories. Accordingly, they generally won't work with the Python interpreters from this PPA. As an exception, pure-Python modules for Python 3 will work, but any compiled extension modules won't.
â”‚  
â”‚  To install 3rd-party Python modules, you should use the common Python packaging tools.  For an introduction into the Python packaging ecosystem and its tools, refer to the Python Packaging User Guide:
â”‚  https://packaging.python.org/installing/
â”‚  
â”‚  Sources
â”‚  =======
â”‚  The package sources are available at:
â”‚  https://github.com/deadsnakes/
â”‚

â”‚  More info: https://launchpad.net/~deadsnakes/+archive/ubuntu/ppa

import torch
import torch_npu

print("=" * 50)
print("æ˜‡è…¾ NPU æµ‹è¯•")
print("=" * 50)

# åˆ›å»ºæµ‹è¯•å¼ é‡å¹¶ç§»åˆ° NPU
print("\n1. åˆ›å»ºå¼ é‡å¹¶ç§»åˆ° NPU...")
x = torch.randn(3, 3)
print(f"CPU å¼ é‡:\n{x}")

x_npu = x.to("npu:0")
print(f"\nNPU å¼ é‡ (è®¾å¤‡: {x_npu.device}):\n{x_npu}")

# åœ¨ NPU ä¸Šè¿›è¡ŒçŸ©é˜µè¿ç®—
print("\n2. åœ¨ NPU ä¸Šæ‰§è¡ŒçŸ©é˜µä¹˜æ³•...")
y_npu = torch.randn(3, 3).to("npu:0")
z_npu = torch.matmul(x_npu, y_npu)
print(f"ç»“æœ:\n{z_npu}")

# æµ‹è¯•æ›´å¤§çš„çŸ©é˜µ
print("\n3. å¤§è§„æ¨¡çŸ©é˜µè¿ç®—æµ‹è¯•...")
a = torch.randn(1000, 1000).to("npu:0")
b = torch.randn(1000, 1000).to("npu:0")

import time
start = time.time()
c = torch.matmul(a, b)
torch_npu.npu.synchronize()
end = time.time()

print(f"1000x1000 çŸ©é˜µä¹˜æ³•è€—æ—¶: {(end-start)*1000:.2f} ms")
print(f"ç»“æœå½¢çŠ¶: {c.shape}, è®¾å¤‡: {c.device}")

# æ˜¾ç¤º NPU ä¿¡æ¯
print("\n4. NPU è®¾å¤‡ä¿¡æ¯:")
for i in range(torch_npu.npu.device_count()):
    print(f"NPU {i}: {torch_npu.npu.get_device_name(i)}")
    print(f"  å†…å­˜å·²åˆ†é…: {torch_npu.npu.memory_allocated(i) / 1024**2:.2f} MB")
    print(f"  å†…å­˜ç¼“å­˜: {torch_npu.npu.memory_reserved(i) / 1024**2:.2f} MB")

print("\n" + "=" * 50)
print("âœ… NPU æµ‹è¯•æˆåŠŸï¼")
print("=" * 50)

import torch
import torch_npu

print("=" * 60)
print("NPU è®¾å¤‡ä¿¡æ¯")
print("=" * 60)

# åˆ—å‡ºæ‰€æœ‰ NPU è®¾å¤‡
for i in range(torch_npu.npu.device_count()):
    print(f"\nNPU {i}:")
    print(f"  åç§°: {torch_npu.npu.get_device_name(i)}")
    props = torch_npu.npu.get_device_properties(i)
    print(f"  å†…å­˜: {props.total_memory / (1024**3):.2f} GB")

print("\n" + "=" * 60)
print("NPU åŸºæœ¬è®¡ç®—æµ‹è¯•")
print("=" * 60)

# æµ‹è¯•åŸºæœ¬å¼ é‡æ“ä½œ
device = torch.device("npu:0")
print(f"\nä½¿ç”¨è®¾å¤‡: {device}")

# åˆ›å»ºå¼ é‡
x = torch.randn(3, 3, device=device)
y = torch.randn(3, 3, device=device)

print(f"\nå¼ é‡ x:\n{x}")
print(f"\nå¼ é‡ y:\n{y}")

# çŸ©é˜µä¹˜æ³•
z = torch.matmul(x, y)
print(f"\nçŸ©é˜µä¹˜æ³• x @ y:\n{z}")

# æµ‹è¯•å¤§çŸ©é˜µæ€§èƒ½
print("\n" + "=" * 60)
print("æ€§èƒ½æµ‹è¯• (1000x1000 çŸ©é˜µä¹˜æ³•)")
print("=" * 60)

import time

size = 1000
a = torch.randn(size, size, device=device)
b = torch.randn(size, size, device=device)

# é¢„çƒ­
for _ in range(3):
    _ = torch.matmul(a, b)

# æµ‹è¯•
start = time.time()
for _ in range(10):
    c = torch.matmul(a, b)
torch_npu.npu.synchronize()  # ç­‰å¾… NPU å®Œæˆ
end = time.time()

print(f"10 æ¬¡çŸ©é˜µä¹˜æ³•è€—æ—¶: {(end - start) * 1000:.2f} ms")
print(f"å¹³å‡æ¯æ¬¡: {(end - start) * 100:.2f} ms")

print("\nâœ… NPU åŸºæœ¬åŠŸèƒ½æµ‹è¯•é€šè¿‡ï¼")

[574] ğŸ¤– åŠ©æ‰‹ - 2025-12-05 09:16:32
ä¼šè¯: 5294cf5b... | æ–‡ä»¶: 5294cf5b-7480-4abf-8715-0f5dd94e3a4c.jsonl
â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€

â”Œâ”€ ğŸ”§ å·¥å…·è°ƒç”¨: Bash [toolu_01EC8D]
â”‚  å‘½ä»¤: source /workspace/dna_study/venv_npu/bin/activate && source /usr/local/Ascend/ascend-toolkit/set_env.sh && python3 << 'EOF'
import torch
import torch_npu
import time

print("=" * 70)
print("åˆ†å­åŠ¨åŠ›å­¦ç›¸å…³è®¡ç®—æµ‹è¯• - NPU åŠ é€Ÿ")
print("=" * 70)

device = torch.device("npu:0")

# æ¨¡æ‹Ÿ DNA åˆ†å­ç³»ç»Ÿ
n_atoms = 1000  # 1000 ä¸ªåŸå­ï¼ˆçº¦ 50bp DNAï¼‰
n_steps = 1000  # 1000 æ­¥æ¨¡æ‹Ÿ

print(f"\nç³»ç»Ÿè§„æ¨¡: {n_atoms} ä¸ªåŸå­")
print(f"æ¨¡æ‹Ÿæ­¥æ•°: {n_steps}")

# åˆå§‹åŒ–åŸå­åæ ‡ (n_atoms, 3)
positions = torch.randn(n_atoms, 3, device=device)
velocities = torch.randn(n_atoms, 3, device=device) * 0.1
forces = torch.zeros(n_atoms, 3, device=device)

# æ¨¡æ‹Ÿå‚æ•°
dt = 0.001  # æ—¶é—´æ­¥é•¿
mass = 1.0

print("\n" + "=" * 70)
print("æµ‹è¯• 1: æˆå¯¹è·ç¦»è®¡ç®—ï¼ˆæ¨¡æ‹Ÿéé”®ç›¸äº’ä½œç”¨ï¼‰")
print("=" * 70)

# è®¡ç®—æ‰€æœ‰åŸå­å¯¹ä¹‹é—´çš„è·ç¦»
start = time.time()
for _ in range(10):
    diff = positions.unsqueeze(1) - positions.unsqueeze(0)  # (n, n, 3)
    distances = torch.sqrt(torch.sum(diff ** 2, dim=-1))  # (n, n)
torch_npu.npu.synchronize()
end = time.time()

print(f"10 æ¬¡è·ç¦»è®¡ç®—è€—æ—¶: {(end - start) * 1000:.2f} ms")
print(f"å¹³å‡æ¯æ¬¡: {(end - start) * 100:.2f} ms")
print(f"è·ç¦»çŸ©é˜µå½¢çŠ¶: {distances.shape}")

print("\n" + "=" * 70)
print("æµ‹è¯• 2: åŠ›è®¡ç®—ï¼ˆç®€åŒ–çš„ Lennard-Jones åŠ¿èƒ½ï¼‰")
print("=" * 70)

start = time.time()
for _ in range(100):
    # ç®€åŒ–çš„åŠ›è®¡ç®—
    diff = positions.unsqueeze(1) - positions.unsqueeze(0)
    r2 = torch.sum(diff ** 2, dim=-1) + 1e-6
    r6 = r2 ** 3
    r12 = r6 ** 2
    
    # Lennard-Jones åŠ›
    force_magnitude = (48.0 / r2) * (1.0 / r12 - 0.5 / r6)
    forces = torch.sum(diff * force_magnitude.unsqueeze(-1), dim=1)
    
torch_npu.npu.synchronize()
end = time.time()

print(f"100 æ¬¡åŠ›è®¡ç®—è€—æ—¶: {(end - start) * 1000:.2f} ms")
print(f"å¹³å‡æ¯æ¬¡: {(end - start) * 10:.2f} ms")

print("\n" + "=" * 70)
print("æµ‹è¯• 3: å®Œæ•´ MD æ­¥éª¤ï¼ˆVelocity Verlet ç§¯åˆ†ï¼‰")
print("=" * 70)

start = time.time()
for step in range(n_steps):
    # Velocity Verlet ç§¯åˆ†
    # åŠæ­¥é€Ÿåº¦æ›´æ–°
    velocities += 0.5 * dt * forces / mass
    
    # ä½ç½®æ›´æ–°
    positions += dt * velocities
    
    # è®¡ç®—æ–°çš„åŠ›ï¼ˆç®€åŒ–ç‰ˆæœ¬ï¼‰
    diff = positions.unsqueeze(1) - positions.unsqueeze(0)
    r2 = torch.sum(diff ** 2, dim=-1) + 1e-6
    r6 = r2 ** 3
    r12 = r6 ** 2
    force_magnitude = (48.0 / r2) * (1.0 / r12 - 0.5 / r6)
    forces = torch.sum(diff * force_magnitude.unsqueeze(-1), dim=1)
    
    # åŠæ­¥é€Ÿåº¦æ›´æ–°
    velocities += 0.5 * dt * forces / mass

torch_npu.npu.synchronize()
end = time.time()

total_time = end - start
print(f"å®Œæˆ {n_steps} æ­¥æ¨¡æ‹Ÿ")
print(f"æ€»è€—æ—¶: {total_time:.2f} ç§’")
print(f"æ¯æ­¥è€—æ—¶: {total_time / n_steps * 1000:.2f} ms")
print(f"æ¨¡æ‹Ÿé€Ÿåº¦: {n_steps / total_time:.2f} æ­¥/ç§’")

# è®¡ç®—åŠ¨èƒ½
kinetic_energy = 0.5 * mass * torch.sum(velocities ** 2)
print(f"\næœ€ç»ˆåŠ¨èƒ½: {kinetic_energy.item():.4f}")

print("\n" + "=" * 70)
print("âœ… NPU åˆ†å­åŠ¨åŠ›å­¦è®¡ç®—æµ‹è¯•å®Œæˆï¼")
print("=" * 70)

â”‚       1â†’"""Base energy functions for DNA1 model.
â”‚       2â†’
â”‚       3â†’These functions are based on the oxDNA1 model paper found here:
â”‚       4â†’https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:b2415bb2-7975-4f59-b5e2-8c022b4a3719/files/mdcac62bc9133143fc05070ed20048c50
â”‚       5â†’"""
â”‚       6â†’
â”‚       7â†’import jax.numpy as jnp
â”‚       8â†’
â”‚       9â†’import jax_dna.energy.potentials as jd_potentials
â”‚      10â†’import jax_dna.utils.types as typ
â”‚      11â†’
â”‚      12â†’
â”‚      13â†’def f1(
â”‚      14â†’    r: typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚      15â†’    r_low: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      16â†’    r_high: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      17â†’    r_c_low: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      18â†’    r_c_high: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      19â†’    eps: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      20â†’    a: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      21â†’    r0: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      22â†’    r_c: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      23â†’    b_low: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      24â†’    b_high: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      25â†’) -> typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      26â†’    """The radial part of the stacking and hydrogen-bonding potentials.
â”‚      27â†’
â”‚      28â†’    This is based on equation 2.7 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      29â†’    """
â”‚      30â†’    oob = jnp.where(
â”‚      31â†’        (r_c_low < r) & (r < r_low),
â”‚      32â†’        eps * jd_potentials.v_smooth(r, b_low, r_c_low),
â”‚      33â†’        jnp.where((r_high < r) & (r < r_c_high), eps * jd_potentials.v_smooth(r, b_high, r_c_high), 0.0),
â”‚      34â†’    )
â”‚      35â†’    return jnp.where(
â”‚      36â†’        (r_low < r) & (r < r_high), jd_potentials.v_morse(r, eps, r0, a) - jd_potentials.v_morse(r_c, eps, r0, a), oob
â”‚      37â†’    )
â”‚      38â†’
â”‚      39â†’
â”‚      40â†’def f2(
â”‚      41â†’    r: typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚      42â†’    r_low: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      43â†’    r_high: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      44â†’    r_c_low: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      45â†’    r_c_high: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      46â†’    k: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      47â†’    r0: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      48â†’    r_c: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      49â†’    b_low: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      50â†’    b_high: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      51â†’) -> typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      52â†’    """The radial part of the cross-stacking and coaxial stacking potentials.
â”‚      53â†’
â”‚      54â†’    This is based on equation 2.8 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      55â†’    """
â”‚      56â†’    oob = jnp.where(
â”‚      57â†’        (r_c_low < r) & (r < r_low),
â”‚      58â†’        k * jd_potentials.v_smooth(r, b_low, r_c_low),
â”‚      59â†’        jnp.where((r_high < r) & (r < r_c_high), k * jd_potentials.v_smooth(r, b_high, r_c_high), 0.0),
â”‚      60â†’    )
â”‚      61â†’    return jnp.where(
â”‚      62â†’        (r_low < r) & (r < r_high), jd_potentials.v_harmonic(r, k, r0) - jd_potentials.v_harmonic(r_c, k, r0), oob
â”‚      63â†’    )
â”‚      64â†’
â”‚      65â†’
â”‚      66â†’def f3(
â”‚      67â†’    r: typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚      68â†’    r_star: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      69â†’    r_c: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      70â†’    eps: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      71â†’    sigma: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      72â†’    b: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      73â†’) -> typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      74â†’    """The radial part of the excluded volume potential.
â”‚      75â†’
â”‚      76â†’    This is based on equation 2.9 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      77â†’    """
â”‚      78â†’    oob = jnp.where((r_star < r) & (r < r_c), eps * jd_potentials.v_smooth(r, b, r_c), 0.0)
â”‚      79â†’    return jnp.where(r < r_star, jd_potentials.v_lj(r, eps, sigma), oob)
â”‚      80â†’
â”‚      81â†’
â”‚      82â†’def f4(
â”‚      83â†’    theta: typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚      84â†’    theta0: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      85â†’    delta_theta_star: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      86â†’    delta_theta_c: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      87â†’    a: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      88â†’    b: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      89â†’) -> typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      90â†’    """The angular modulation factor used in stacking, hydrogen-bonding, cross-stacking and coaxial stacking.
â”‚      91â†’
â”‚      92â†’    This is based on equation 2.10 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      93â†’    """
â”‚      94â†’    oob = jnp.where(
â”‚      95â†’        (theta0 - delta_theta_c < theta) & (theta < theta0 - delta_theta_star),
â”‚      96â†’        jd_potentials.v_smooth(theta, b, theta0 - delta_theta_c),
â”‚      97â†’        jnp.where(
â”‚      98â†’            (theta0 + delta_theta_star < theta) & (theta < theta0 + delta_theta_c),
â”‚      99â†’            jd_potentials.v_smooth(theta, b, theta0 + delta_theta_c),
â”‚     100â†’            0.0,
â”‚  
â”‚  <system-reminder>
â”‚  Whenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.
â”‚  </system-reminder>

â”‚          ("r", "r_low", "r_high", "r_c_low", "r_c_high", "eps", "a", "r0", "r_c", "b_low", "b_high"),

â”‚      def test_f1(

â”‚          """Test the f1 base function.
â”‚

â”‚          1. r_low < r < r_high

â”Œâ”€ âœ… å·¥å…·è¾“å‡º [toolu_01PgUS]
â”‚       1â†’"""This module contains the potential energy functions used in the oxDNA DNA1 model."""
â”‚       2â†’
â”‚       3â†’import jax.numpy as jnp
â”‚       4â†’
â”‚       5â†’import jax_dna.utils.types as jd_types
â”‚       6â†’
â”‚       7â†’# https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:b2415bb2-7975-4f59-b5e2-8c022b4a3719/files/mdcac62bc9133143fc05070ed20048c50
â”‚       8â†’# Section 2.4.1
â”‚       9â†’
â”‚      10â†’
â”‚      11â†’def v_fene(
â”‚      12â†’    r: jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR, eps: jd_types.Scalar, r0: jd_types.Scalar, delt: jd_types.Scalar
â”‚      13â†’) -> jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      14â†’    """FENE spring (used to connect backbones).
â”‚      15â†’
â”‚      16â†’    This is based on equation 2.1 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      17â†’    """
â”‚      18â†’    x = (r - r0) ** 2 / delt**2
â”‚      19â†’    return -eps / 2.0 * jnp.log(1 - x)
â”‚      20â†’
â”‚      21â†’
â”‚      22â†’def v_morse(
â”‚      23â†’    r: jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚      24â†’    eps: jd_types.Scalar,
â”‚      25â†’    r0: jd_types.Scalar,
â”‚      26â†’    a: jd_types.Scalar,
â”‚      27â†’) -> jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      28â†’    """Morse potential (used for stacking and H-bonding).
â”‚      29â†’
â”‚      30â†’    This is based on equation 2.2 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      31â†’    """
â”‚      32â†’    x = -(r - r0) * a
â”‚      33â†’    return eps * (1 - jnp.exp(x)) ** 2
â”‚      34â†’
â”‚      35â†’
â”‚      36â†’def v_harmonic(
â”‚      37â†’    r: jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚      38â†’    k: jd_types.Scalar,
â”‚      39â†’    r0: jd_types.Scalar,
â”‚      40â†’) -> jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      41â†’    """Harmonic potential (used for cross-stacking and coaxial stacking).
â”‚      42â†’
â”‚      43â†’    This is based on equation 2.3 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      44â†’    """
â”‚      45â†’    return k / 2 * (r - r0) ** 2
â”‚      46â†’
â”‚      47â†’
â”‚      48â†’def v_lj(r: jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR, eps: jd_types.Scalar, sigma: jd_types.Scalar) -> jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      49â†’    """Lennard - Jones potential (used for soft repulsion).
â”‚      50â†’
â”‚      51â†’    This is based on equation 2.4 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      52â†’    """
â”‚      53â†’    x = (sigma / r) ** 12 - (sigma / r) ** 6
â”‚      54â†’    return 4 * eps * x
â”‚      55â†’
â”‚      56â†’
â”‚      57â†’def v_mod(theta: jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR, a: jd_types.Scalar, theta0: jd_types.Scalar) -> jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      58â†’    """Quadratic terms (used for modulation).
â”‚      59â†’
â”‚      60â†’    This is based on equation 2.5 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      61â†’    """
â”‚      62â†’    return 1 - a * (theta - theta0) ** 2
â”‚      63â†’
â”‚      64â†’
â”‚      65â†’def v_smooth(x: jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR, b: jd_types.Scalar, x_c: jd_types.Scalar) -> jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      66â†’    """Quadratic smoothing terms for truncation.
â”‚      67â†’
â”‚      68â†’    This is based on equation 2.6 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      69â†’    """
â”‚      70â†’    return b * (x_c - x) ** 2
â”‚      71â†’

â”‚      40â†’Arr_N = jaxtyp.Array  # jaxtyp.Float[jaxtyp.Array, "#n"]
â”‚      41â†’Arr_Nucleotide = jaxtyp.Float[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_nucleotides"]
â”‚      42â†’Arr_Nucleotide_Int = jaxtyp.Int[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_nucleotides"]
â”‚      43â†’Arr_Nucleotide_2 = jaxtyp.Float[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_nucleotides 2"]
â”‚      44â†’Arr_Nucleotide_2_Int = jaxtyp.Int[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_nucleotides 2"]
â”‚      45â†’Arr_Nucleotide_3 = jaxtyp.Float[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_nucleotides 3"]
â”‚      46â†’Arr_Nucleotide_4 = jaxtyp.Float[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_nucleotides 4"]
â”‚      47â†’Arr_Nucleotide_15 = jaxtyp.Float[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_nucleotides 15"]
â”‚      48â†’Arr_Bonded_Neighbors = jaxtyp.Int[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_bonded_pairs"]
â”‚      49â†’Arr_Unbonded_Neighbors = jaxtyp.Int[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_unbonded_pairs"]
â”‚      50â†’Arr_Bonded_Neighbors_2 = jaxtyp.Int[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_bonded_pairs 2"]
â”‚      51â†’Arr_Unbonded_Neighbors_2 = jaxtyp.Int[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_unbonded_pairs 2"]
â”‚      52â†’Arr_States = jaxtyp.Int[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_states"]
â”‚      53â†’Arr_States_3 = jaxtyp.Int[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_states 3"]
â”‚      54â†’
â”‚      55â†’ARR_OR_SCALAR = Arr_N | Scalar
â”‚      56â†’
â”‚      57â†’Arr_Unpaired = jaxtyp.Int[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_unpaired"]
â”‚      58â†’Arr_Unpaired_Pseq = jaxtyp.Float[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_unpaired 4"]
â”‚      59â†’Arr_Bp = jaxtyp.Int[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_bp 2"]
â”‚      60â†’Arr_Bp_Pseq = jaxtyp.Float[jaxtyp.Array, "#n_bp 4"]
â”‚      61â†’Discrete_Sequence = Arr_Nucleotide_Int
â”‚      62â†’Probabilistic_Sequence = tuple[Arr_Unpaired_Pseq, Arr_Bp_Pseq]
â”‚      63â†’Sequence = Discrete_Sequence | Probabilistic_Sequence
â”‚      64â†’
â”‚      65â†’MetaData = dict[str, Any]

ä¼šè¯: 5294cf5b... | æ–‡ä»¶: 5294cf5b-7480-4abf-8715-0f5dd94e3a4c.jsonl
â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€

â”Œâ”€ âœ… å·¥å…·è¾“å‡º [toolu_01PgUS]
â”‚       1â†’"""This module contains the potential energy functions used in the oxDNA DNA1 model."""
â”‚       2â†’
â”‚       3â†’import jax.numpy as jnp
â”‚       4â†’
â”‚       5â†’import jax_dna.utils.types as jd_types
â”‚       6â†’
â”‚       7â†’# https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:b2415bb2-7975-4f59-b5e2-8c022b4a3719/files/mdcac62bc9133143fc05070ed20048c50
â”‚       8â†’# Section 2.4.1
â”‚       9â†’
â”‚      10â†’
â”‚      11â†’def v_fene(
â”‚      12â†’    r: jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR, eps: jd_types.Scalar, r0: jd_types.Scalar, delt: jd_types.Scalar
â”‚      13â†’) -> jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      14â†’    """FENE spring (used to connect backbones).
â”‚      15â†’
â”‚      16â†’    This is based on equation 2.1 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      17â†’    """
â”‚      18â†’    x = (r - r0) ** 2 / delt**2
â”‚      19â†’    return -eps / 2.0 * jnp.log(1 - x)
â”‚      20â†’
â”‚      21â†’
â”‚      22â†’def v_morse(
â”‚      23â†’    r: jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚      24â†’    eps: jd_types.Scalar,
â”‚      25â†’    r0: jd_types.Scalar,
â”‚      26â†’    a: jd_types.Scalar,
â”‚      27â†’) -> jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      28â†’    """Morse potential (used for stacking and H-bonding).
â”‚      29â†’
â”‚      30â†’    This is based on equation 2.2 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      31â†’    """
â”‚      32â†’    x = -(r - r0) * a
â”‚      33â†’    return eps * (1 - jnp.exp(x)) ** 2
â”‚      34â†’
â”‚      35â†’
â”‚      36â†’def v_harmonic(
â”‚      37â†’    r: jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚      38â†’    k: jd_types.Scalar,
â”‚      39â†’    r0: jd_types.Scalar,
â”‚      40â†’) -> jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      41â†’    """Harmonic potential (used for cross-stacking and coaxial stacking).
â”‚      42â†’
â”‚      43â†’    This is based on equation 2.3 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      44â†’    """
â”‚      45â†’    return k / 2 * (r - r0) ** 2
â”‚      46â†’
â”‚      47â†’
â”‚      48â†’def v_lj(r: jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR, eps: jd_types.Scalar, sigma: jd_types.Scalar) -> jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      49â†’    """Lennard - Jones potential (used for soft repulsion).
â”‚      50â†’
â”‚      51â†’    This is based on equation 2.4 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      52â†’    """
â”‚      53â†’    x = (sigma / r) ** 12 - (sigma / r) ** 6
â”‚      54â†’    return 4 * eps * x
â”‚      55â†’
â”‚      56â†’
â”‚      57â†’def v_mod(theta: jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR, a: jd_types.Scalar, theta0: jd_types.Scalar) -> jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      58â†’    """Quadratic terms (used for modulation).
â”‚      59â†’
â”‚      60â†’    This is based on equation 2.5 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      61â†’    """
â”‚      62â†’    return 1 - a * (theta - theta0) ** 2
â”‚      63â†’
â”‚      64â†’
â”‚      65â†’def v_smooth(x: jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR, b: jd_types.Scalar, x_c: jd_types.Scalar) -> jd_types.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      66â†’    """Quadratic smoothing terms for truncation.
â”‚      67â†’
â”‚      68â†’    This is based on equation 2.6 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      69â†’    """
â”‚      70â†’    return b * (x_c - x) ** 2
â”‚      71â†’

â”‚      22â†’        )

â”‚      28â†’    return float(sp.parsing.sympy_parser.parse_expr("k / 2 * (r - r0)**2").evalf(subs={"r": r, "k": k, "r0": r0}))
â”‚      29â†’
â”‚      30â†’
â”‚      31â†’def v_lj(r: float, eps: float, sigma: float) -> float:

â”‚      33â†’    return float(

â”‚      36â†’        )

â”‚      45â†’        )
â”‚      46â†’    )
â”‚      47â†’
â”‚      48â†’

â”‚      51â†’    return float(sp.parsing.sympy_parser.parse_expr("b * (x_c - x)**2").evalf(subs={"x": x, "b": b, "x_c": x_c}))

       - `v_harmonic()` - Harmonic for cross-stacking
       - `v_lj()` - Lennard-Jones for repulsion
       - `v_mod()` - Quadratic modulation
       - `v_smooth()` - Truncation smoothing
     ```python
     def v_morse(r, eps, r0, a):
         r_tensor = torch.as_tensor(r) if not isinstance(r, torch.Tensor) else r
         x = -(r_tensor - r0) * a
         return eps * (1 - torch.exp(x)) ** 2
     ```

â”‚      11â†’        sp.parsing.sympy_parser.parse_expr("-eps / 2 * log(1 - (r-r0)**2 / delt**2)").evalf(
â”‚      12â†’            subs={"r": r, "eps": eps, "r0": r0, "delt": delt}
â”‚      13â†’        )
â”‚      14â†’    )
â”‚      15â†’
â”‚      16â†’
â”‚      17â†’def v_morse(r: float, eps: float, r0: float, a: float) -> float:
â”‚      18â†’    """String form of Equation 2.2 from the oxDNA paper."""
â”‚      19â†’    return float(
â”‚      20â†’        sp.parsing.sympy_parser.parse_expr("eps * (1 - exp(-(r-r0)*a))**2").evalf(
â”‚      21â†’            subs={"r": r, "eps": eps, "r0": r0, "a": a}
â”‚      22â†’        )
â”‚      23â†’    )
â”‚      24â†’
â”‚      25â†’
â”‚      26â†’def v_harmonic(r: float, k: float, r0: float) -> float:
â”‚      27â†’    """String form of Equation 2.3 from the oxDNA paper."""
â”‚      28â†’    return float(sp.parsing.sympy_parser.parse_expr("k / 2 * (r - r0)**2").evalf(subs={"r": r, "k": k, "r0": r0}))
â”‚      29â†’
â”‚      30â†’
â”‚      31â†’def v_lj(r: float, eps: float, sigma: float) -> float:
â”‚      32â†’    """String form of the Lennard-Jones potential."""
â”‚      33â†’    return float(
â”‚      34â†’        sp.parsing.sympy_parser.parse_expr("4 * eps * ((sigma / r)**12 - (sigma / r)**6)").evalf(
â”‚      35â†’            subs={"r": r, "eps": eps, "sigma": sigma}
â”‚      36â†’        )
â”‚      37â†’    )
â”‚      38â†’
â”‚      39â†’
â”‚      40â†’def v_mod(theta: float, a: float, theta0: float) -> float:
â”‚      41â†’    """String form of the modified potential."""
â”‚      42â†’    return float(
â”‚      43â†’        sp.parsing.sympy_parser.parse_expr("1 - a * (theta - theta0)**2").evalf(
â”‚      44â†’            subs={"theta": theta, "a": a, "theta0": theta0}
â”‚      45â†’        )
â”‚      46â†’    )
â”‚      47â†’
â”‚      48â†’
â”‚      49â†’def v_smooth(x: float, b: float, x_c: float) -> float:
â”‚      50â†’    """String form of the smooth potential."""
â”‚      51â†’    return float(sp.parsing.sympy_parser.parse_expr("b * (x_c - x)**2").evalf(subs={"x": x, "b": b, "x_c": x_c}))
â”‚      52â†’
â”‚

â”‚      57â†’        return opts.get(x, defaults)
â”‚      58â†’
â”‚      59â†’    default_stacking_opts = tuple(set(default_config["stacking"].keys()) - {"kT", "ss_stack_weights"})

[1024] ğŸ‘¤ ç”¨æˆ· - 2025-12-05 11:29:19
ä¼šè¯: 86df67fc... | æ–‡ä»¶: 86df67fc-814b-49f8-8cbc-689e7ac2cd89.jsonl
â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€

â”Œâ”€ âœ… å·¥å…·è¾“å‡º [toolu_01RBS7]
â”‚       1â†’"""Base energy functions for DNA1 model.
â”‚       2â†’
â”‚       3â†’These functions are based on the oxDNA1 model paper found here:
â”‚       4â†’https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:b2415bb2-7975-4f59-b5e2-8c022b4a3719/files/mdcac62bc9133143fc05070ed20048c50
â”‚       5â†’"""
â”‚       6â†’
â”‚       7â†’import jax.numpy as jnp
â”‚       8â†’
â”‚       9â†’import jax_dna.energy.potentials as jd_potentials
â”‚      10â†’import jax_dna.utils.types as typ
â”‚      11â†’
â”‚      12â†’
â”‚      13â†’def f1(
â”‚      14â†’    r: typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚      15â†’    r_low: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      16â†’    r_high: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      17â†’    r_c_low: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      18â†’    r_c_high: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      19â†’    eps: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      20â†’    a: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      21â†’    r0: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      22â†’    r_c: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      23â†’    b_low: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      24â†’    b_high: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      25â†’) -> typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      26â†’    """The radial part of the stacking and hydrogen-bonding potentials.
â”‚      27â†’
â”‚      28â†’    This is based on equation 2.7 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      29â†’    """
â”‚      30â†’    oob = jnp.where(
â”‚      31â†’        (r_c_low < r) & (r < r_low),
â”‚      32â†’        eps * jd_potentials.v_smooth(r, b_low, r_c_low),
â”‚      33â†’        jnp.where((r_high < r) & (r < r_c_high), eps * jd_potentials.v_smooth(r, b_high, r_c_high), 0.0),
â”‚      34â†’    )
â”‚      35â†’    return jnp.where(
â”‚      36â†’        (r_low < r) & (r < r_high), jd_potentials.v_morse(r, eps, r0, a) - jd_potentials.v_morse(r_c, eps, r0, a), oob
â”‚      37â†’    )
â”‚      38â†’
â”‚      39â†’
â”‚      40â†’def f2(
â”‚      41â†’    r: typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚      42â†’    r_low: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      43â†’    r_high: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      44â†’    r_c_low: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      45â†’    r_c_high: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      46â†’    k: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      47â†’    r0: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      48â†’    r_c: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      49â†’    b_low: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      50â†’    b_high: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      51â†’) -> typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      52â†’    """The radial part of the cross-stacking and coaxial stacking potentials.
â”‚      53â†’
â”‚      54â†’    This is based on equation 2.8 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      55â†’    """
â”‚      56â†’    oob = jnp.where(
â”‚      57â†’        (r_c_low < r) & (r < r_low),
â”‚      58â†’        k * jd_potentials.v_smooth(r, b_low, r_c_low),
â”‚      59â†’        jnp.where((r_high < r) & (r < r_c_high), k * jd_potentials.v_smooth(r, b_high, r_c_high), 0.0),
â”‚      60â†’    )
â”‚      61â†’    return jnp.where(
â”‚      62â†’        (r_low < r) & (r < r_high), jd_potentials.v_harmonic(r, k, r0) - jd_potentials.v_harmonic(r_c, k, r0), oob
â”‚      63â†’    )
â”‚      64â†’
â”‚      65â†’
â”‚      66â†’def f3(
â”‚      67â†’    r: typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚      68â†’    r_star: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      69â†’    r_c: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      70â†’    eps: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      71â†’    sigma: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      72â†’    b: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      73â†’) -> typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      74â†’    """The radial part of the excluded volume potential.
â”‚      75â†’
â”‚      76â†’    This is based on equation 2.9 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      77â†’    """
â”‚      78â†’    oob = jnp.where((r_star < r) & (r < r_c), eps * jd_potentials.v_smooth(r, b, r_c), 0.0)
â”‚      79â†’    return jnp.where(r < r_star, jd_potentials.v_lj(r, eps, sigma), oob)
â”‚      80â†’
â”‚      81â†’
â”‚      82â†’def f4(
â”‚      83â†’    theta: typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚      84â†’    theta0: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      85â†’    delta_theta_star: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      86â†’    delta_theta_c: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      87â†’    a: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      88â†’    b: typ.Scalar,
â”‚      89â†’) -> typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚      90â†’    """The angular modulation factor used in stacking, hydrogen-bonding, cross-stacking and coaxial stacking.
â”‚      91â†’
â”‚      92â†’    This is based on equation 2.10 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      93â†’    """
â”‚      94â†’    oob = jnp.where(
â”‚      95â†’        (theta0 - delta_theta_c < theta) & (theta < theta0 - delta_theta_star),
â”‚      96â†’        jd_potentials.v_smooth(theta, b, theta0 - delta_theta_c),
â”‚      97â†’        jnp.where(
â”‚      98â†’            (theta0 + delta_theta_star < theta) & (theta < theta0 + delta_theta_c),
â”‚      99â†’            jd_potentials.v_smooth(theta, b, theta0 + delta_theta_c),
â”‚     100â†’            0.0,
â”‚     101â†’        ),
â”‚     102â†’    )
â”‚     103â†’    return jnp.where(
â”‚     104â†’        (theta0 - delta_theta_star < theta) & (theta < theta0 + delta_theta_star),
â”‚     105â†’        jd_potentials.v_mod(theta, a, theta0),
â”‚     106â†’        oob,
â”‚     107â†’    )
â”‚     108â†’
â”‚     109â†’
â”‚     110â†’def f5(
â”‚     111â†’    x: typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚     112â†’    x_star: typ.Scalar,
â”‚     113â†’    x_c: typ.Scalar,
â”‚     114â†’    a: typ.Scalar,
â”‚     115â†’    b: typ.Scalar,
â”‚     116â†’) -> typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚     117â†’    """Another modulating term which is used to impose right-handedness (effectively a one-sided modulation).
â”‚     118â†’
â”‚     119â†’    This is based on equation 2.11 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚     120â†’    """
â”‚     121â†’    return jnp.where(
â”‚     122â†’        x > 0.0,
â”‚     123â†’        1.0,
â”‚     124â†’        jnp.where(
â”‚     125â†’            (x_star < x) & (x < 0.0),
â”‚     126â†’            jd_potentials.v_mod(x, a, 0),
â”‚     127â†’            jnp.where((x_c < x) & (x < x_star), jd_potentials.v_smooth(x, b, x_c), 0.0),
â”‚     128â†’        ),
â”‚     129â†’    )
â”‚     130â†’
â”‚

[1026] ğŸ¤– åŠ©æ‰‹ - 2025-12-05 11:29:32
ä¼šè¯: 86df67fc... | æ–‡ä»¶: 86df67fc-814b-49f8-8cbc-689e7ac2cd89.jsonl
â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€

â•”â•â• ğŸ’­ æ€è€ƒè¿‡ç¨‹ â•â•â•—
â•‘ I can see that:1. DNA1 module has ~2700 lines of code across 13 files
â•‘ 2. base_functions.py defines 5 fundamental functions (f1-f5) that build on top of the basic potentials
â•‘ 3. These functions use conditional logic with jnp.where() which maps to torch.where()4. The module has dependencies on:
â•‘    - BaseEnergyFunction and BaseConfiguration (base classes I haven't seen yet)
â•‘    - Configuration classes for each energy component
â•‘    - TOML config file parsing

â•‘ This is getting complex. I can see that the DNA1 energy module depends on:
â•‘ 
â•‘ 1. `base.py` - base classes for energy functions2. `configuration.py` - configuration management3. `jax_md` - JAX molecular dynamics library (rigid bodies, spaces, etc.)
â•‘ 4. `chex` - JAX data structures library
â•‘ 
â•‘ This is a significant architectural dependency. The migration will require:
â•‘ 1. Either finding PyTorch equivalents for jax_md and chex
â•‘ 2. Or reimplementing the necessary parts
â•‘ 
â•‘ Let me take a step back and think about the overall strategy. The user wants complete migration, but this is very complex. I should:
â•‘ 
â•‘ 1. Check how much of the code actually depends on jax_md vs. just using basic JAX operations
â•‘ 2. See if I can migrate the simpler, more self-contained parts first3. Look at what the tests actually test
â•‘

â”‚      37â†’    def pairwise_energies(
â”‚      38â†’        self,
â”‚      39â†’        body: je_base.BaseNucleotide,
â”‚      40â†’        bonded_neighbors: typ.Arr_Bonded_Neighbors_2,
â”‚      41â†’    ) -> typ.Arr_Bonded_Neighbors:
â”‚      42â†’        """Computes the FENE energy for each bonded pair."""
â”‚      43â†’        nn_i = bonded_neighbors[:, 0]
â”‚      44â†’        nn_j = bonded_neighbors[:, 1]
â”‚      45â†’
â”‚      46â†’        dr_back_nn = self.displacement_mapped(body.back_sites[nn_i], body.back_sites[nn_j])
â”‚      47â†’        r_back_nn = jnp.linalg.norm(dr_back_nn, axis=1)
â”‚      48â†’
â”‚      49â†’        return dna1_interactions.v_fene_smooth(
â”‚      50â†’            r_back_nn,
â”‚      51â†’            self.params.eps_backbone,
â”‚      52â†’            self.params.r0_backbone,
â”‚      53â†’            self.params.delta_backbone,
â”‚      54â†’            self.params.fmax,
â”‚      55â†’            self.params.finf,
â”‚      56â†’        )
â”‚      57â†’
â”‚      58â†’    @override
â”‚      59â†’    def __call__(

â”‚      65â†’    ) -> typ.Scalar:
â”‚      66â†’        dgs = self.pairwise_energies(body, bonded_neighbors)
â”‚      67â†’        return dgs.sum()

â”‚       1â†’"""Configuration class for energy models."""
â”‚       2â†’
â”‚       3â†’import warnings
â”‚       4â†’from typing import Any, Union
â”‚       5â†’
â”‚       6â†’import chex

â”‚       8â†’import jax_dna.utils.types as jdt
â”‚       9â†’
â”‚      10â†’ERR_MISSING_REQUIRED_PARAMS = "Required properties {props} are not initialized."
â”‚      11â†’ERR_OPT_DEPENDENT_PARAMS = "Only {req_params} permitted for optimization, but found {given_params}"
â”‚      12â†’WARN_INIT_PARAMS_NOT_IMPLEMENTED = "init_params not implemented"
â”‚      13â†’WARN_DEPENDENT_PARAMS_NOT_INITIALIZED = "Dependent parameters not initialized"
â”‚      14â†’
â”‚      15â†’
â”‚      16â†’@chex.dataclass(frozen=True)
â”‚      17â†’class BaseConfiguration:
â”‚      18â†’    """Base class for configuration classes.
â”‚      19â†’
â”‚      20â†’    This class should not be used directly.
â”‚      21â†’
â”‚      22â†’    Parameters:
â”‚      23â†’        params_to_optimize (tuple[str]): parameters to optimize
â”‚      24â†’        required_params (tuple[str]): required parameters
â”‚      25â†’        non_optimizable_required_params (tuple[str]): required parameters that are not optimizable
â”‚      26â†’        dependent_params (tuple[str]): dependent parameters, these are calculated from the independent parameters
â”‚      27â†’        OPT_ALL (tuple[str]): CONSTANT, is a wild card for all parameters
â”‚      28â†’    """
â”‚      29â†’
â”‚      30â†’    params_to_optimize: tuple[str] = ()
â”‚      31â†’    required_params: tuple[str] = ()
â”‚      32â†’    non_optimizable_required_params: tuple[str] = ()
â”‚      33â†’    dependent_params: tuple[str] = ()
â”‚      34â†’    OPT_ALL: tuple[str] = ("*",)
â”‚      35â†’
â”‚      36â†’    @property
â”‚      37â†’    def opt_params(self) -> dict[str, jdt.Scalar]:
â”‚      38â†’        """Returns the parameters to optimize."""
â”‚      39â†’        if self.params_to_optimize == self.OPT_ALL:
â”‚      40â†’            params = {
â”‚      41â†’                k: v
â”‚      42â†’                for k, v in self.items()
â”‚      43â†’                if (k in self.required_params) and (k not in self.non_optimizable_required_params)
â”‚      44â†’            }
â”‚      45â†’        else:
â”‚      46â†’            params = {k: v for k, v in self.items() if k in self.params_to_optimize}
â”‚      47â†’
â”‚      48â†’        return params
â”‚      49â†’
â”‚      50â†’    def __post_init__(self) -> None:
â”‚      51â†’        """Checks validity of the configuration."""
â”‚      52â†’        non_initialized_props = [param for param in self.required_params if getattr(self, param) is None]
â”‚      53â†’        if non_initialized_props:
â”‚      54â†’            raise ValueError(ERR_MISSING_REQUIRED_PARAMS.format(props=",".join(non_initialized_props)))
â”‚      55â†’
â”‚      56â†’        optimizable_params = set(self.required_params) - set(self.non_optimizable_required_params)
â”‚      57â†’        unoptimizable_params = set(self.params_to_optimize) - optimizable_params
â”‚      58â†’        if unoptimizable_params and unoptimizable_params != set(self.OPT_ALL):
â”‚      59â†’            raise ValueError(
â”‚      60â†’                ERR_OPT_DEPENDENT_PARAMS.format(
â”‚      61â†’                    req_params=",".join(sorted(optimizable_params)),
â”‚      62â†’                    given_params=",".join(sorted(unoptimizable_params)),
â”‚      63â†’                )
â”‚      64â†’            )
â”‚      65â†’
â”‚      66â†’    def init_params(self) -> "BaseConfiguration":
â”‚      67â†’        """Initializes the dependent parameters in configuration.
â”‚      68â†’
â”‚      69â†’        Should be implemented in the subclass if dependent parameters are present.
â”‚      70â†’        """
â”‚      71â†’        warnings.warn(WARN_INIT_PARAMS_NOT_IMPLEMENTED, stacklevel=1)
â”‚      72â†’        return self
â”‚      73â†’
â”‚      74â†’    @classmethod
â”‚      75â†’    def from_dict(cls, params: dict[str, float], params_to_optimize: tuple[str] = ()) -> "BaseConfiguration":
â”‚      76â†’        """Creates a configuration from a dictionary."""
â”‚      77â†’        return cls(**(params | {"params_to_optimize": params_to_optimize}))
â”‚      78â†’
â”‚      79â†’    def to_dictionary(
â”‚      80â†’        self,
â”‚      81â†’        *,
â”‚      82â†’        include_dependent: bool,
â”‚      83â†’        exclude_non_optimizable: bool,
â”‚      84â†’    ) -> dict[str, jdt.ARR_OR_SCALAR]:
â”‚      85â†’        """Converts the configuration to a dictionary."""
â”‚      86â†’        params = {k: getattr(self, k) for k in self.required_params}
â”‚      87â†’
â”‚      88â†’        if include_dependent:
â”‚      89â†’            for k in self.dependent_params:
â”‚      90â†’                if val := getattr(self, k):
â”‚      91â†’                    params[k] = val
â”‚      92â†’                else:
â”‚      93â†’                    warnings.warn(WARN_DEPENDENT_PARAMS_NOT_INITIALIZED, stacklevel=1)
â”‚      94â†’
â”‚      95â†’        if exclude_non_optimizable:
â”‚      96â†’            for k in self.non_optimizable_required_params:
â”‚      97â†’                params.pop(k, None)
â”‚      98â†’
â”‚      99â†’        return params
â”‚     100â†’
â”‚     101â†’    def __merge__baseconfig(self, other: "BaseConfiguration") -> "BaseConfiguration":
â”‚     102â†’        """Merges two BaseConfiguration objects."""
â”‚     103â†’        filtered = {k: v for k, v in other.items() if v is not None}
â”‚     104â†’        return self.__merge__dict(filtered)
â”‚     105â†’
â”‚     106â†’    def __merge__dict(self, other: dict[str, Any]) -> "BaseConfiguration":
â”‚     107â†’        """Merges a dictionary with the configuration."""
â”‚     108â†’        return self.replace(**other)
â”‚     109â†’
â”‚     110â†’    # python doesn't like using the bar for type hints when inside the class, use Union for now
â”‚     111â†’    def __or__(self, other: Union["BaseConfiguration", dict[str, jdt.ARR_OR_SCALAR]]) -> "BaseConfiguration":
â”‚     112â†’        """Convenience method to merge a configuration or a dictionary with the current configuration.
â”‚     113â†’
â”‚     114â†’        Returns a new configuration object.
â”‚     115â†’        """
â”‚     116â†’        if isinstance(other, BaseConfiguration):
â”‚     117â†’            merge_fn = self.__merge__baseconfig
â”‚     118â†’        elif isinstance(other, dict):
â”‚     119â†’            merge_fn = self.__merge__dict
â”‚     120â†’        else:
â”‚     121â†’            return NotImplemented
â”‚     122â†’
â”‚     123â†’        return merge_fn(other)

â•”â•â• ğŸ’­ æ€è€ƒè¿‡ç¨‹ â•â•â•—
â•‘ Now I see the pattern more clearly. The jax-dna project uses:
â•‘ 
â•‘ 1. **chex.dataclass** - for frozen dataclasses (like Python's dataclasses)
â•‘ 2. **jax_md.rigid_body** - for molecular dynamics simulations3. **Base classes** - BaseEnergyFunction, BaseConfiguration4. **Displacement functions** - from jax_md.space for periodic boundary conditionsThis is a significant architectural challenge. The complete migration would require:
â•‘ 
â•‘ 1. Replacing `chex.dataclass` with Python `dataclasses.dataclass` 
â•‘ 2. Replacing `jax_md` rigid body mechanics - this is a big one
â•‘ 3. Migrating all the energy interaction functionsGiven the complexity and the user's explicit request for "å½»å½»åº•åº•çš„è¿ç§»æ•´ä¸ªé¡¹ç›®", I need to make a strategic decision. Let me check what the test files actually test - maybe I can focus on the core computational parts first:
â•šâ•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•

[1048] ğŸ‘¤ ç”¨æˆ· - 2025-12-05 11:30:27
ä¼šè¯: 86df67fc... | æ–‡ä»¶: 86df67fc-814b-49f8-8cbc-689e7ac2cd89.jsonl
â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€

â”Œâ”€ âœ… å·¥å…·è¾“å‡º [toolu_01QrV6]
â”‚       1â†’"""Smoothing functions for the base functions in DNA1 model.
â”‚       2â†’
â”‚       3â†’functional forms from oxDNA paper
â”‚       4â†’https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:b2415bb2-7975-4f59-b5e2-8c022b4a3719/files/mdcac62bc9133143fc05070ed20048c50
â”‚       5â†’# Section 2.4.1
â”‚       6â†’"""
â”‚       7â†’
â”‚       8â†’import jax.numpy as jnp
â”‚       9â†’
â”‚      10â†’import jax_dna.utils.types as typ
â”‚      11â†’
â”‚      12â†’
â”‚      13â†’def _solve_f1_b(x: typ.Scalar, a: typ.Scalar, x0: typ.Scalar, xc: typ.Scalar) -> typ.Scalar:
â”‚      14â†’    """Solve for the smoothing parameter b in the f1 smoothing function."""
â”‚      15â†’    return (
â”‚      16â†’        a**2
â”‚      17â†’        * (
â”‚      18â†’            -jnp.exp(a * (3 * x0 + 2 * xc))
â”‚      19â†’            + 2 * jnp.exp(a * (x + 2 * x0 + 2 * xc))
â”‚      20â†’            - jnp.exp(a * (2 * x + x0 + 2 * xc))
â”‚      21â†’        )
â”‚      22â†’        * jnp.exp(-2 * a * x)
â”‚      23â†’        / (
â”‚      24â†’            2 * jnp.exp(a * (x + 2 * xc))
â”‚      25â†’            + jnp.exp(a * (2 * x + x0))
â”‚      26â†’            - 2 * jnp.exp(a * (2 * x + xc))
â”‚      27â†’            - jnp.exp(a * (x0 + 2 * xc))
â”‚      28â†’        )
â”‚      29â†’    )
â”‚      30â†’
â”‚      31â†’
â”‚      32â†’def _solve_f1_xc_star(x: typ.Scalar, a: typ.Scalar, x0: typ.Scalar, xc: typ.Scalar) -> typ.Scalar:
â”‚      33â†’    """Solve for the smoothing parameter xc_star in the f1 smoothing function."""
â”‚      34â†’    return (
â”‚      35â†’        (
â”‚      36â†’            a * x * jnp.exp(a * (x + 2 * xc))
â”‚      37â†’            - a * x * jnp.exp(a * (x0 + 2 * xc))
â”‚      38â†’            + 2 * jnp.exp(a * (x + 2 * xc))
â”‚      39â†’            + jnp.exp(a * (2 * x + x0))
â”‚      40â†’            - 2 * jnp.exp(a * (2 * x + xc))
â”‚      41â†’            - jnp.exp(a * (x0 + 2 * xc))
â”‚      42â†’        )
â”‚      43â†’        * jnp.exp(-2 * a * xc)
â”‚      44â†’        / (a * (jnp.exp(a * x) - jnp.exp(a * x0)))
â”‚      45â†’    )
â”‚      46â†’
â”‚      47â†’
â”‚      48â†’def get_f1_smoothing_params(
â”‚      49â†’    x0: typ.Scalar, a: typ.Scalar, xc: typ.Scalar, x_low: typ.Scalar, x_high: typ.Scalar
â”‚      50â†’) -> tuple[typ.Scalar, typ.Scalar, typ.Scalar, typ.Scalar]:
â”‚      51â†’    """Get the smoothing parameters for the f1 smoothing function."""
â”‚      52â†’    solved_b_low = _solve_f1_b(x_low, a, x0, xc)
â”‚      53â†’    solved_b_high = _solve_f1_b(x_high, a, x0, xc)
â”‚      54â†’
â”‚      55â†’    solved_xc_low = _solve_f1_xc_star(x_low, a, x0, xc)
â”‚      56â†’    solved_xc_high = _solve_f1_xc_star(x_high, a, x0, xc)
â”‚      57â†’
â”‚      58â†’    return solved_b_low, solved_xc_low, solved_b_high, solved_xc_high
â”‚      59â†’
â”‚      60â†’
â”‚      61â†’def _solve_f2_b(x: typ.Scalar, x0: typ.Scalar, xc: typ.Scalar) -> typ.Scalar:
â”‚      62â†’    """Solve for the smoothing parameter b in the f2 smoothing function."""
â”‚      63â†’    return (x - x0) ** 2 / (2 * (x - xc) * (x - 2 * x0 + xc))
â”‚      64â†’
â”‚      65â†’
â”‚      66â†’def _solve_f2_xc_star(x: typ.Scalar, x0: typ.Scalar, xc: typ.Scalar) -> typ.Scalar:
â”‚      67â†’    """Solve for the smoothing parameter xc_star in the f2 smoothing function."""
â”‚      68â†’    return (x * x0 - 2 * x0 * xc + xc**2) / (x - x0)
â”‚      69â†’
â”‚      70â†’
â”‚      71â†’def get_f2_smoothing_params(
â”‚      72â†’    x0: typ.Scalar, xc: typ.Scalar, x_low: typ.Scalar, x_high: typ.Scalar
â”‚      73â†’) -> tuple[typ.Scalar, typ.Scalar, typ.Scalar, typ.Scalar]:
â”‚      74â†’    """Get the smoothing parameters for the f2 smoothing function."""
â”‚      75â†’    solved_b_low = _solve_f2_b(x_low, x0, xc)
â”‚      76â†’    solved_b_high = _solve_f2_b(x_high, x0, xc)
â”‚      77â†’
â”‚      78â†’    solved_xc_low = _solve_f2_xc_star(x_low, x0, xc)
â”‚      79â†’    solved_xc_high = _solve_f2_xc_star(x_high, x0, xc)
â”‚      80â†’
â”‚      81â†’    return solved_b_low, solved_xc_low, solved_b_high, solved_xc_high
â”‚      82â†’
â”‚      83â†’
â”‚      84â†’def _solve_f3_b(x: typ.Scalar, sigma: typ.Scalar) -> typ.Scalar:
â”‚      85â†’    """Solve for the smoothing parameter b in the f3 smoothing function."""
â”‚      86â†’    return (
â”‚      87â†’        -36
â”‚      88â†’        * sigma**6
â”‚      89â†’        * (-2 * sigma**6 + x**6) ** 2
â”‚      90â†’        / (x**14 * (-sigma + x) * (sigma + x) * (sigma**2 - sigma * x + x**2) * (sigma**2 + sigma * x + x**2))
â”‚      91â†’    )
â”‚      92â†’
â”‚      93â†’
â”‚      94â†’def _solve_f3_xc(x: typ.Scalar, sigma: typ.Scalar) -> typ.Scalar:
â”‚      95â†’    """Solve for the smoothing parameter xc in the f3 smoothing function."""
â”‚      96â†’    return x * (-7 * sigma**6 + 4 * x**6) / (3 * (-2 * sigma**6 + x**6))
â”‚      97â†’
â”‚      98â†’
â”‚      99â†’def get_f3_smoothing_params(r_star: typ.Scalar, sigma: typ.Scalar) -> tuple[typ.Scalar, typ.Scalar]:
â”‚     100â†’    """Get the smoothing parameters for the f3 smoothing function."""
â”‚     101â†’    solved_b = _solve_f3_b(r_star, sigma)
â”‚     102â†’    solved_xc = _solve_f3_xc(r_star, sigma)
â”‚     103â†’
â”‚     104â†’    return solved_b, solved_xc
â”‚     105â†’
â”‚     106â†’
â”‚     107â†’def _solve_f4_b(x: typ.Scalar, x0: typ.Scalar, a: typ.Scalar) -> typ.Scalar:
â”‚     108â†’    """Solve for the smoothing parameter b in the f4 smoothing function."""
â”‚     109â†’    return -(a**2) * (x - x0) ** 2 / (a * x**2 - 2 * a * x * x0 + a * x0**2 - 1)
â”‚     110â†’
â”‚     111â†’
â”‚     112â†’def _solve_f4_xc(x: typ.Scalar, x0: typ.Scalar, a: typ.Scalar) -> typ.Scalar:
â”‚     113â†’    """Solve for the smoothing parameter xc in the f4 smoothing function."""
â”‚     114â†’    return (-a * x * x0 + a * x0**2 - 1) / (a * (-x + x0))
â”‚     115â†’
â”‚     116â†’
â”‚     117â†’def get_f4_smoothing_params(a: typ.Scalar, x0: typ.Scalar, delta_x_star: typ.Scalar) -> tuple[typ.Scalar, typ.Scalar]:
â”‚     118â†’    """Get the smoothing parameters for the f4 smoothing function."""
â”‚     119â†’    solved_b_plus = _solve_f4_b(x0 + delta_x_star, x0, a)
â”‚     120â†’
â”‚     121â†’    solved_xc_plus = _solve_f4_xc(x0 + delta_x_star, x0, a)
â”‚     122â†’    solved_delta_xc_plus = solved_xc_plus - x0
â”‚     123â†’
â”‚     124â†’    return solved_b_plus, solved_delta_xc_plus
â”‚     125â†’
â”‚     126â†’
â”‚     127â†’def _solve_f5_b(x: typ.Scalar, x0: typ.Scalar, a: typ.Scalar) -> typ.Scalar:
â”‚     128â†’    """Solve for the smoothing parameter b in the f5 smoothing function."""
â”‚     129â†’    return -(a**2) * (x - x0) ** 2 / (a * x**2 - 2 * a * x * x0 + a * x0**2 - 1)
â”‚     130â†’
â”‚     131â†’
â”‚     132â†’def _solve_f5_xc(x: typ.Scalar, x0: typ.Scalar, a: typ.Scalar) -> typ.Scalar:
â”‚     133â†’    """Solve for the smoothing parameter xc in the f5 smoothing function."""
â”‚     134â†’    return (a * x * x0 - a * x0**2 + 1) / (a * (x - x0))
â”‚     135â†’
â”‚     136â†’
â”‚     137â†’def get_f5_smoothing_params(a: typ.Scalar, x_star: typ.Scalar) -> tuple[typ.Scalar, typ.Scalar]:
â”‚     138â†’    """Get the smoothing parameters for the f5 smoothing function."""
â”‚     139â†’    solved_b = _solve_f5_b(x_star, 0.0, a)
â”‚     140â†’    solved_xc = _solve_f5_xc(x_star, 0.0, a)
â”‚     141â†’
â”‚     142â†’    return solved_b, solved_xc
â”‚     143â†’

â”‚      17â†’    eps: float,
â”‚      18â†’    a: float,
â”‚      19â†’    r0: float,
â”‚      20â†’    r_c: float,
â”‚      21â†’    b_low: float,
â”‚      22â†’    b_high: float,
â”‚      23â†’) -> float:
â”‚      24â†’    """This is a symbolic representation of the f1 base function.
â”‚      25â†’
â”‚      26â†’    Equation 2.7 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      27â†’
â”‚      28â†’    This function has described has 4 cases:
â”‚      29â†’    1. r_low < r < r_high
â”‚      30â†’    2. r_c_low < r < r_low
â”‚      31â†’    3. r_high < r < r_c_high
â”‚      32â†’    4. Otherwise
â”‚      33â†’    """
â”‚      34â†’    value = 0
â”‚      35â†’    if r_low < r < r_high:
â”‚      36â†’        value = sp.v_morse(r, eps, r0, a) - sp.v_morse(r_c, eps, r0, a)
â”‚      37â†’    elif r_c_low < r < r_low:
â”‚      38â†’        value = eps * sp.v_smooth(r, b_low, r_c_low)
â”‚      39â†’    elif r_high < r < r_c_high:
â”‚      40â†’        value = eps * sp.v_smooth(r, b_high, r_c_high)
â”‚      41â†’
â”‚      42â†’    return value
â”‚      43â†’
â”‚      44â†’
â”‚      45â†’def f2(
â”‚      46â†’    r: float,
â”‚      47â†’    r_low: float,
â”‚      48â†’    r_high: float,
â”‚      49â†’    r_c_low: float,
â”‚      50â†’    r_c_high: float,
â”‚      51â†’    k: float,
â”‚      52â†’    r0: float,
â”‚      53â†’    r_c: float,
â”‚      54â†’    b_low: float,
â”‚      55â†’    b_high: float,
â”‚      56â†’) -> float:
â”‚      57â†’    """This is a symbolic representation of the f1 base function.
â”‚      58â†’
â”‚      59â†’    Equation 2.8 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      60â†’
â”‚      61â†’    This function has described has 4 cases:
â”‚      62â†’    1. r_low < r < r_high
â”‚      63â†’    2. r_c_low < r < r_low
â”‚      64â†’    3. r_high < r < r_c_high
â”‚      65â†’    4. Otherwise
â”‚      66â†’    """
â”‚      67â†’    value = 0
â”‚      68â†’    if r_low < r < r_high:
â”‚      69â†’        value = sp.v_harmonic(r, k, r0) - sp.v_harmonic(r_c, k, r0)
â”‚      70â†’    elif r_c_low < r < r_low:
â”‚      71â†’        value = k * sp.v_smooth(r, b_low, r_c_low)
â”‚      72â†’    elif r_high < r < r_c_high:
â”‚      73â†’        value = k * sp.v_smooth(r, b_high, r_c_high)
â”‚      74â†’
â”‚      75â†’    return value
â”‚      76â†’
â”‚      77â†’
â”‚      78â†’def f3(
â”‚      79â†’    r: float,
â”‚      80â†’    r_star: float,
â”‚      81â†’    r_c: float,
â”‚      82â†’    eps: float,
â”‚      83â†’    sigma: float,
â”‚      84â†’    b: float,
â”‚      85â†’) -> float:
â”‚      86â†’    """The radial part of the excluded volume potential.
â”‚      87â†’
â”‚      88â†’    This is based on equation 2.9 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚      89â†’
â”‚      90â†’    This function has described has 3 cases:
â”‚      91â†’    1. r < r_star
â”‚      92â†’    2. r_star < r < r_c
â”‚      93â†’    3. Otherwise
â”‚      94â†’    """
â”‚      95â†’    value = 0
â”‚      96â†’    if r < r_star:
â”‚      97â†’        value = sp.v_lj(r, eps, sigma)
â”‚      98â†’    elif r_star < r < r_c:
â”‚      99â†’        value = eps * sp.v_smooth(r, b, r_c)
â”‚     100â†’
â”‚     101â†’    return value
â”‚     102â†’
â”‚     103â†’
â”‚     104â†’def f4(
â”‚     105â†’    theta: typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR,
â”‚     106â†’    theta0: typ.Scalar,
â”‚     107â†’    delta_theta_star: typ.Scalar,
â”‚     108â†’    delta_theta_c: typ.Scalar,
â”‚     109â†’    a: typ.Scalar,
â”‚     110â†’    b: typ.Scalar,
â”‚     111â†’) -> typ.ARR_OR_SCALAR:
â”‚     112â†’    """The angular modulation factor used in stacking, hydrogen-bonding, cross-stacking and coaxial stacking.
â”‚     113â†’
â”‚     114â†’    This is based on equation 2.10 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚     115â†’
â”‚     116â†’    This function has 4 cases:
â”‚     117â†’    1. theta0 - delta_theta_star < theta < theta0 + delta_theta_star
â”‚     118â†’    2  theta0 - delta_theta_c < theta < theta0 - delta_theta_star
â”‚     119â†’    3. theta0 + delta_theta_star < theta < theta0 + delta_theta_c
â”‚     120â†’    4. Otherwise
â”‚     121â†’    """
â”‚     122â†’
â”‚     123â†’    value = 0
â”‚     124â†’    if theta0 - delta_theta_star < theta < theta0 + delta_theta_star:
â”‚     125â†’        value = sp.v_mod(theta, a, theta0)
â”‚     126â†’    elif theta0 - delta_theta_c < theta < theta0 - delta_theta_star:
â”‚     127â†’        value = sp.v_smooth(theta, b, theta0 - delta_theta_c)
â”‚     128â†’    elif theta0 + delta_theta_star < theta < theta0 + delta_theta_c:
â”‚     129â†’        value = sp.v_smooth(theta, b, theta0 + delta_theta_c)
â”‚     130â†’
â”‚     131â†’    return value
â”‚     132â†’
â”‚     133â†’
â”‚     134â†’def f5(
â”‚     135â†’    x: float,
â”‚     136â†’    x_star: float,
â”‚     137â†’    x_c: float,
â”‚     138â†’    a: float,
â”‚     139â†’    b: float,
â”‚     140â†’) -> float:
â”‚     141â†’    """Another modulating term which is used to impose right-handedness (effectively a one-sided modulation).
â”‚     142â†’
â”‚     143â†’    This is based on equation 2.11 from the oxDNA paper.
â”‚     144â†’
â”‚     145â†’    This functionn has 4 cases:
â”‚     146â†’    1. x > 0
â”‚     147â†’    2. x_star < x < 0
â”‚     148â†’    3. x_c < x < x_star
â”‚     149â†’    4. Otherwise
â”‚     150â†’    """
â”‚     151â†’    value = 0
â”‚     152â†’    if x > 0:
â”‚     153â†’        value = 1
â”‚     154â†’    elif x_star < x < 0:
â”‚     155â†’        value = sp.v_mod(x, a, 0)
â”‚     156â†’    elif x_c < x < x_star:
â”‚     157â†’        value = sp.v_smooth(x, b, x_c)
â”‚     158â†’
â”‚     159â†’    return value
â”‚     160â†’
â”‚
